rComments: Very caring and flexible with deadlines. Clearly knows a lot and cares a lot about the subject but lectures are dry and difficult to follow. Lots of choice for assignment formats and topics, and tries to ensure that students can make personal and practical links to the content. I didn't learn very much but at least she was kind.

Professor McCutcheon's lectures are a bit dry and she was not great with technology so I wouldn't recommend if it's online, however, she is very flexible with due dates and really wants students to improve their writing and succeed in the course. There was a lot of papers, but she was a fair marker and super accessible for questions
teacherRatingTags: ['Accessible outside class', 'So many papers', 'Gives good feedback']

rComments: While the professor is a nice person, a large amount of the assigned work is framed in such a way that seems almost un-academic. It may be personal opinion, but a major component of a history class shouldn't be taking Twitter and modern media as important sources.

Okay, I took this class because I needed an elective in my fourth year. Please tell me why this class required more assignments than all of my fourth year classes together? Major research paper and take home final are both at a 3000 word minimum. It's not a fourth year class. I don't recommend unless you like being stressed all the time.
teacherRatingTags: ['Gives good feedback', 'So many papers', 'Lots of homework']

rComments: Prof McCutcheon is extremely knowledgeable and passionate about her course's subject matter. She is also the kindest and most engaging prof I have ever had in my 4 years at Univeristy of Ottawa. Took two courses with her this semester and learned more in them than I have in my whole degree! She's the best!
So many assignments! But she is flexible with deadlines. Lectures were a bit scattered, and assignments were unclear at times. Nice enough as a person, but wouldn't recommend as a prof.

Professor McCutcheon is incredibly caring about her students and very passionate about history. However, her lectures were very disorganised and a little dull. She would go into details that weren't very important, and then not go into depth into more major topics. The course felt very piecemeal, it didn't feel organised by theme or big picture.

Professor McCutcheon seemed like a nice lady and was clearly passionate about history. However, her lectures were dry, vague, and repetitive. She didn't explain things in-depth, was often disorganized, and read off her notes. She made what was supposed to be an interesting class boring...

McCutcheon slams your semester with papers, so much so that you are constantly stressed when to turn them in. Requires 5 short papers, in addition to a long. Half the time she seems to be extremely disorganized. I cannot emphasize enough how monotone and dull her lectures are. She manages to make an interesting course into an endless blah.
teacherRatingTags: ['So many papers', 'Lots of homework', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Dr. McCutcheon is one of the best profs a uOttawa by far! She records her lectures if you can't make it. Everything is online. She even has a facebook group for each class which makes discussion much easier.  Her material is interesting and engaging. Assignments are decent and final take home was fair. 10/10 would recommend.

McCutcheon is so incredibly sweet. She's very lenient with late assignments, and you only actually have to complete 4/6 of her workshops. She encourages discussion and creativity, and is in general just very kind and upbeat. Content is a little dry (subject's fault, not hers) but she manages to make it fun. Take -home exam. Really cool lady.

I have had her for multiple class; She has a lot of assignments, which is good because if you do poorly on one thing you can still do well in the course and she gives good feedback. However, her class is a LOT of work and lectures ARE mandatory. The final take home for a first year class ended up being around 25 pages, so definitely a lot of work.

Uses online textbook so you don't have to buy which is a bonus, but she posts power points and notes on foreign websites and highly encourages students to sign up/ use them as well... I don't understand why she didn't simply post them on blackboard instead. Lectures were boring and the workload was pretty heavy but generally pretty easy
Amazing prof who cares deeply about her students. Good with extensions and new ideas. Very supportive and is open to learning from her students.

She's a good prof, she clearly cares very much about her topic. She explains things well and the class has a clear narrative. She really cares for her students and she was always there for me in a crisis. Make SURE you attend classes or watch the podcasts. Papers require lots of research, so start early.

She's a pretty easy marker, but as a third year in a first year class, I found that the papers she assigned were really long. They were longer then some of my upper year classes. Overall good teacher.

Prof. McCutcheon is such a sweetheart! Sometimes the lectures can be a bit dry, but that's just early (and not as hyped as US) Canadian history for you. She gives you access to tools you will need to use as a future history undergraduate student, and she has NO EXAMS! She also has a Facebook group (I wish more Profs did this)

No tests! Four large assignments including a final assignment instead of an exam. Everything is online and she allows you to send in questions online live during lectures. Even has a Facebook group for students.  Very informative and tries to include lecture material students are interested in.

Biggest mistake. She gives so many assignments to the point where you solely focus on her class and neglect your others. The slides are repetitive and contain fluff. TA was cute, but was surprisingly a very hard marker. McCutcheon is a very sweet lady, but it will be my last time taking her classes. Tooooooo many assignments.
Clear expectatkonsand a wealth of knowledge. By far one of the most caring and well-read history profs.

She is the best Prof I have ever had, and I've been fortunate to have many great teachers. Prof. McCutcheon wants to know that you are learning, and is willing to negotiate deadlines if you approach her and explain why you need an extension. Detailed instructions for assignments, and very helpful with feedback and advice. She's the best!

Professor McCutcheon was HANDS DOWN the best Prof I have ever had! I have had her for a few courses. She is kind & understanding and genuinely wants her students to do well. Her feedback on everything is very helpful. There were a lot of assignments, but more so to keep you on top of your work! Definitely recommend! She rocks.

Incredible prof - she is there for the students! She is very knowledgeable about Canadian history. She is more than willing to give you guidance with your essays and class assignments, you just have to ask!
Nice lady but the class is boring and repetitive. The class is composed of many assignments at least once every other week but she marks generously.

For the "Making of Canada" I actually didn't mind her lectures, but the interactive aspect was somewhat tedious. The two assignments for the class were, respectively, a bit off topic and a bit demanding for a 1st year survey course. She was quite approachable and helpful, though I'd advise against taking the class with her.
She was a good professor but her lectures contain too much info, they almost sound like she's reading a script.  But she was helpful though if you needed help with your essay.

Amazing prof!!! You just need to do the work! She had attendance and participation marks for 20%, easiest marks of your life!!! she is awesome, totally there for you if you need it too!Very knowledgeable and will extend deadlines too.

Extremely boring & highly demanding class. I have had demanding 4th year seminars that were less work than her class. Extremely unrealistic expectations of students when this class is not optional for most. Expectations were also a little unclear. Hated this class.

The most boring class I have ever taken. Prof simply reads slides, which are very general. Exams are very specific and lectures are not helpful for studying. Refused to use virtual campus for the first few months. Very funny and helpful (provided insight for my paper) outside of class.

Her lectures were basically her reading her facts sheet. Very boring, and very unclear since she never emphasized what was important and what was not. Beyond that, Virtual Campus notes were USELESS. Tests were very specific, and thus difficult. Overall, quite unfair. I did not have a good time in this I class. I would not recommend it to anyone.

Had her for Making of Canada, worst class I've ever taken. so boring, goes way to fast, doesnt use virtual campus, and overall a horrible professor, havent learned anything. She's a nice lady, just AVOID taking this course by all means. And I love history, overall I don't hate it. This was just so awful.
She's very nice and helpful outside of classes, but her lectures are ridiculously boring - I'd rather read the textbook which is saying something.

She seems to know a lot and is very helpfull if you contact her outside of class. My overall problem was that the class was SOOOO BORING I wanted to cry. She goes over the same thing again and again... had a very hard time getting the class into the subject material.

Very nice and personable, VERY helpful if you talk to her about your problems with the material. I just *loved* her laugh!  Very comitted to her students and very knowledgeable.  I could listen to her all day...
Two sexy Thumbs up!!!
The class was hard but you learn a lot. She knows what she's talking about. I gained a lot of good research skills. Overall, she's clear about what she expects from you and is very helpful.
One of the most useless people I've ever had the displeasure of having as a "teacher".
Really helpful and enthusiastic, loves to have fun while getting through a lot of material. enjoys her own subject and tries to make the class enjoyable too. lots of readings though!
